05683nam a22006735i 9780231850650DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802318506507 a10.7312/kuc-169822doi  a(DE-B1597)458401  a(OCoLC)984520585  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN1995.9.E96 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/61109438223  aAP 44949qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7516:70804aThe Struggle for Form :bPerspectives on Polish Avant-Garde Film, 1916–1989 /ced. by Kamila Kuc, Michael O'Pray.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Contributors -- tChapter One. The Themersons and the Polish Avant-Garde: Warsaw – Paris – London -- t‘The inexpressible unearthly beauty of the cinematograph’: The impact of Polish Futurism on the First Polish avant-Garde Films -- tExcerpts from the ‘Archives’ of the Polish Avant-Garde -- tChapter Three. The Search for a ‘More Spacious Form’: Experimental Trends in Polish Documentary (1945–1989) -- tChapter Four. Avant-Garde and the Thaw: Experimentation in Polish Cinema of the 1950s and 1960s -- tChapter Five. Avant-Garde Exploits: The Cultural Highs and Lows of Polish Émigré Cinema -- tChapter Six. The Mechanical Imagination – Creativity of Machines: Film Form Workshop 1970–1977 -- tThe 1980s: From Specificity to the New Tradition – Avant-Garde Film and Video art in Poland -- tFilm Form Workshop Statements -- tChapter Eight. A Rebellion à la polonaise -- tBibliography -- tFilmography -- tIndex of Names -- tIntroduction0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first comprehensive English-language account of the Polish avant-garde film, from its beginnings in the early decades of the last century to the collapse of communism in 1989. Taking a broad understanding of avant-garde film, this collection includes writings on the pioneering work of the internationally-acclaimed Franciszka and Stefan Themerson; the Polish Futurists' (Jalu Kurek, Anatol Stern) engagement with film; the Thaw and animation (Jan Lenica and Walerian Borowczyk, Andrzej Pawlowski, Zbigniew Rybczynski); documentary (Natalia Brzozowska, Kazimierz Karabasz, Wojciech Wiszniewski), Polish émigré filmmakers (Roman Polanski, Jerzy Skolimowski, Andrzej Zulawski) as well as essays and documentation on the highly influential Film Form Workshop (Józef Robakowski, Ryszard Wasko, Wojciech Bruszewski). Including a mix of historical writings from early film magazines with commissioned essays, this book constitutes an important source on the rich, complex and diverse history of the Polish film avant-garde, which is presented from the perspective of both British (A. L. Rees, Jonathan Owen, Michael O'Pray) and Polish (Marcin Gizycki, Ryszard Kluszczynski, Kamila Kuc) authorities on the subject. This book is thus an indispensable introduction to the theories and practices of critically important avant-garde artists and filmmakers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zPolandxHistoryy20th century. 0aExperimental filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aExperimental filmszPolandxHistoryy20th century. 0aPerforming artsxFilm and VideoxHistory and criticism. 0aPerforming artsxReference. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aGiżycki, Marcin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJazdon, Mikołaj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKluszczyński, Ryszard W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/